λεκάνη , dish , pan + μαντεία , divination  )  is a form of divination using a dish , usually of water , which , like many ancient forms of divination , has multiple forms .

If a distinction is to be made between divination and fortune-telling , divination has a more formal or ritualistic element and often contains a more social character , usually in a religious context , as seen in traditional African medicine .
This is in stark contrast with earlier forms of the divination which used clay bowls or basins .

In the context of the oracle bones of ancient China , which chiefly utilized both scapulae and the plastrons of turtle , scapulimancy is sometimes used in a very broad sense to jointly refer to both scapulimancy and plastromancy  (  similar divination using plastrons  )  .
